  "summary": "Inspector Taverner interrogates Mr. Leonidis regarding his father’s will and family dynamics. Mr. Leonidis explains that his father made a new will in 1945, leaving his stepmother £100,000 and dividing the remainder into three equal parts for himself, his brother, and his brother's three grandchildren. He denies having a financial motive for his father's death, noting that his father provides for him and his wife. Regarding his father's marriage, Mr. Leonidis describes the couple as happy but admits he considers the marriage unwise. He also clarifies that Lawrence Brown is a private tutor for his children, Philip and Josephine, and lives on the other side of the house due to available space. He denies any knowledge of an intimate relationship between Mr. Brown and his stepmother, Brenda.\n\nTaverner then interviews Margaret West (Mrs. Philip), a former actress with a reputation for being independent and a prankster. Margaret states that at the time of the tragedy, she was in London attending a fashion show and having drinks. She claims to have loved her husband and notes that she and Brenda do not see each other often because they have little in common. When Taverner asks about a potential romantic relationship between Brenda and Lawrence Brown, Margaret defends Brenda’s character and states she has seen no such signs, asserting that she only recognizes Brenda as her husband's wife. The Inspector concludes the interview and moves to discuss the servants.",
